        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>CORRELATOR SETUP

We request a Band 8 observation covering the CI line at 609.14 microns (492.161 GHz) with ~0.6 km/s spectral resolution. This will 
provide 17 spectral resolution elements across the expected emission velocity range (~10 km/s), revealing the orbital motion of the gas. 
The bandwidth of the spectral line observation is 1142 km/s (1.875 GHz), completely encompassing the expected emission. Our spectral 
setup will simultaneously provide a dust continuum map at ~618 microns (487 GHz) using the other three basebands. To maximize the 
sensitivity of these observations, the three spectral windows were set to be 2 GHz wide with low spectral resolution (31.25 MHz). We 
also placed them so that the LO frequency falls in the center of a deep atmospheric absorption feature, with the sidebands outside 
the feature.

IMAGING

Since the largest gas structure we expect is 5 arcsec in diameter, we require only a single pointing and an ACA observation is not 
needed. We chose an angular resolution of 0.5 arcsec, sufficient to resolve any gas clumps and providing 10 spatial resolution elements 
across the whole gas structure.

SENSITIVITY

The representative frequency for our sensitivity calculations is the frequency of the CI line (492.161 GHz). The expected peak flux 
density per beam for CI emission near the star is 114 mJy, adopting a line width for this emission equal to that measured from the 
line-of-sight CI absorption features (1.5 km/s). Our sensitivity goal is an RMS noise of 11.4 mJy/beam, providing a 10 sigma 
detection of the relatively faint emission near the star. Other parts of the gas structure will likely be brighter. According to the 
Sensitivity Calculator in the ALMA Observing Tool, this goal can be reached in 41 minutes of on-source time. The total array time 
including system-defined calibration observations and overheads is 1.5 hours.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
